    fullDescription: "The Terme di Caracalla are among the most impressive and least crowded ancient ruins in Rome — a vast public bathing complex opened around AD 216 that could accommodate some 1,600 people at once. Far more than a place to wash, these thermae were a leisure city under one roof, with a cold-water frigidarium, a warm tepidarium, a domed hot caldarium, an Olympic-sized swimming pool, gymnasiums, libraries and gardens, all heated by an underground network of furnaces and served by their own aqueduct branch. Today the towering brick walls still soar 30 metres high, and patches of the original mosaic floors survive, giving a real sense of the imperial scale. Because they sit slightly off the main tourist trail near the Aventine Hill, you can often explore in relative peace. In summer the ruins become a magical open-air stage for the Rome Opera's productions, floodlit against the night sky. Good multimedia reconstructions and occasional virtual-reality headsets help you picture the marble-clad splendour. Allow an hour, and combine it with the nearby Aventine and its famous keyhole view of St Peter's dome.",
