    fullDescription: "The Via Appia Antica, begun in 312 BC, was ancient Rome's most important road — the 'regina viarum' that ran all the way to Brindisi on the Adriatic and along which armies marched, trade flowed and, infamously, the rebel slaves of Spartacus were crucified. Roman law forbade burials inside the city, so the road out of town became lined with grand tombs, mausoleums and, later, the underground Christian catacombs. Today a stretch of it is protected as a regional park, and walking or cycling the original basalt paving beneath towering umbrella pines, past crumbling tombs and green fields, is one of the most atmospheric and least touristy things to do in Rome. Highlights include the Catacombs of San Callisto and San Sebastiano, the round tomb of Cecilia Metella and the ruins of the Villa dei Quintili. The road is at its best on Sundays, when much of it closes to cars. Hire a bike at the park entrance, pack a picnic and give it half a day; it feels a world away from the crowded centre.",
