    fullDescription: "Basilica di Santa Maria Maggiore is the largest of Rome's churches dedicated to the Virgin Mary and one of the four great papal basilicas, founded in the fifth century after, legend says, a miraculous August snowfall marked out its footprint on the Esquiline Hill — an event still commemorated each year with a shower of white petals. It has been continuously in use for over 1,500 years, which makes its layers of art extraordinary: the fifth-century mosaics running high along the nave depicting Old Testament scenes are among the oldest in the city, while the flat coffered ceiling is said to be gilded with the very first gold brought back from the Americas, a gift from the Spanish crown. Below lie the tomb of the great Baroque sculptor Bernini and a relic said to be from the manger of the Nativity. It became the burial place of Pope Francis in 2025. Entry to the basilica is free; a small fee gives access to the museum, the ancient underground level and the loggia mosaics. It sits an easy walk from Termini station, so it is convenient to slot in on arrival or departure.",
