    fullDescription: "The Natale di Roma marks the mythical birthday of the city — 21 April 753 BC, the date the ancient Romans held that Romulus founded Rome — and it remains one of the most colourful and distinctive events in the calendar. Each year the anniversary is celebrated with a spectacular series of historical re-enactments staged by costumed groups such as the Gruppo Storico Romano: hundreds of participants in full Roman military and civilian dress parade through the streets and the archaeological heart of the city, with legionaries, gladiators, senators and vestal virgins on the march, mock battles and gladiatorial combats, and ceremonies around the Circus Maximus, the Imperial Forums and the Campidoglio. There are usually torch-lit processions, historical markets and cultural events over several days around the date. It is a wonderful, atmospheric time to be in the city, bringing ancient Rome vividly to life against the backdrop of the very monuments where its history unfolded. As an added bonus, many of Rome's civic museums often offer free admission on 21 April to mark the occasion, so it is worth checking which sites are participating. The main spectacles centre on the Circus Maximus and Via dei Fori Imperiali; arrive early to get a good vantage point along the parade route, as they draw large, enthusiastic crowds.",
