    fullDescription: "As the spiritual centre of the Catholic world, Rome observes Holy Week and Easter with a solemnity and scale found nowhere else, and the period draws pilgrims and visitors from across the globe to the Vatican. The week building up to Easter Sunday is filled with major liturgies led by the Pope: on Holy Thursday and Good Friday the ceremonies culminate in the moving torch-lit Via Crucis (Way of the Cross) procession at the Colosseum on Good Friday evening, when the Pope leads meditations on the Stations of the Cross against the floodlit ancient arena. On Easter Sunday, an enormous crowd fills St Peter's Square for the papal Mass, followed at noon by the Pope's 'Urbi et Orbi' blessing to the city and the world from the basilica's central balcony. These events are free to attend, though some Vatican liturgies inside St Peter's require (free) tickets obtained in advance, and space in the square fills hours ahead, so arrive very early or watch on the big screens. Beyond the religious ceremonies, expect the city to be busy and hotels pricey around this movable feast, whose date shifts each year between late March and April. Even for non-religious visitors, the spectacle, the pilgrims and the atmosphere make it a remarkable, if crowded, time to experience Rome.",
