    fullDescription: "The Festa del Cinema di Roma (Rome Film Fest), held each October, is the capital's answer to Venice and Cannes — a major international film festival that has grown steadily in prestige since its founding in 2006. Centred on Renzo Piano's striking Auditorium Parco della Musica in the Flaminio district, it runs for around ten days and presents a rich programme of world and Italian premieres, competition films, retrospectives, restored classics, documentaries and 'close encounter' public talks with directors and stars, drawing celebrities and cinephiles alike, so keep an eye out for red-carpet arrivals and famous faces. Unlike some industry-only events, a good portion of the festival is genuinely open to the public, with tickets to screenings and events available to ordinary film fans, making it a rewarding time for movie lovers to visit the city. The Auditorium itself, a cluster of scarab-shaped concert halls set around an open-air amphitheatre, is worth seeing in its own right and hosts music and cultural events year-round. October is also an excellent month to be in Rome weather-wise, with pleasant shoulder-season conditions and lighter crowds at the main sights. Check the festival's official programme and ticketing in advance if you want to attend screenings, as popular titles and star events sell out quickly.",
