    fullDescription: "Festa della Repubblica, celebrated on 2 June, is Italy's national day, commemorating the 1946 referendum in which Italians voted to abolish the monarchy and become a republic, and Rome hosts the country's grandest official celebrations. The centrepiece is a large military parade down Via dei Fori Imperiali, the avenue running past the ancient Roman Forums, reviewed by the President of the Republic and attended by the highest offices of state; ranks of the armed forces, historic units, bands and veterans march through the monumental heart of the city. The ceremonies begin with the President laying a wreath at the Altare della Patria (the Vittoriano monument) at Piazza Venezia in honour of the Unknown Soldier. A spectacular highlight is the flypast by the Frecce Tricolori, the Italian Air Force aerobatic display team, which streaks over the centre trailing plumes of green, white and red smoke in the colours of the Italian flag — a thrilling sight against the sky above the Forums. The Quirinale Palace and its gardens, the presidential residence, are often opened to the public around this time. It is a free, patriotic spectacle and a public holiday, so expect a festive atmosphere, closed offices and road closures around the parade route; arrive early along Via dei Fori Imperiali for a good view.",
