    fullDescription: "The Christmas season in Rome is long, atmospheric and deeply traditional, stretching from Advent all the way to Epiphany on 6 January. The city dresses up with festive lights along the main shopping streets, a giant Christmas tree and an enormous nativity scene in St Peter's Square, and above all the beloved Italian presepi — elaborate nativity scenes displayed in churches across the city, from tiny hand-crafted tableaux to life-size figures, with a long-running exhibition of them near St Peter's. On Christmas Eve the Pope celebrates midnight Mass in St Peter's Basilica (free tickets required in advance), and on Christmas Day delivers the 'Urbi et Orbi' blessing from the basilica balcony to crowds in the square. A distinctly Roman highlight is the Christmas market that traditionally fills Piazza Navona with stalls of toys, sweets and decorations. The season climaxes with Epiphany on 6 January, celebrating the arrival of the Magi and, in Italian folklore, the visit of La Befana, a kindly old witch who brings sweets to good children and coal to the naughty — she appears at markets and events, especially around Piazza Navona. Expect the holiday fortnight to be busy and hotel prices high, but the city looks beautiful, and the blend of religious devotion, twinkling lights and folk tradition makes a winter Christmas visit to Rome genuinely magical.",
